Hi, finally had some time to tackle on this! BTW, I have used the excellent [Gdi Leak Detector](https://www.codeproject.com/Tips/20264/GDI-Leak-Detector-A-special-debugger-to-detect-and) tool (credits to the author!) with a MSVC build of Gtk.

The issue is quite simple:

[gtkcssshadowvalue.c : draw_shadow_corner()](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gtk/blob/3.22.30/gtk/gtkcssshadowvalue.c#L688)
uses a GHashTable to collect images of varying size as they are created, so that they are reused later.
The fact is, with shadow animations, that hash table literally explodes with many thousands of cairo surfaces.

Maybe the indexing is too precise, consider that keys in that hash table are CornerMask structures:

```c
typedef struct {
  double radius;
  GtkRoundedBoxCorner corner;
} CornerMask;
```
```c
struct _GtkRoundedBoxCorner {
  double                   horizontal;
  double                   vertical;
};
```
and the comparing function
```c
static gboolean
corner_mask_equal (CornerMask *mask1,
                   CornerMask *mask2)
{
  return
    mask1->radius == mask2->radius &&
    mask1->corner.horizontal == mask2->corner.horizontal &&
    mask1->corner.vertical == mask2->corner.vertical;
}
```
checks for equality of doubles

When animating shadows from none up to a certain size, that function can collect surfaces for potentially every triplet of doubles between extremal values.

