It looks like Vala is generating a destroy call because the delegates aren't marked as unowned in the gio-2.0.vapi.

The first step is to manually change the gio-2.0.vapi to test this. Use:

    [CCode (cheader_filename = "gio/gio.h", has_type_id = false)]
    public struct ActionEntry {
        public weak string name;
        [Version (deprecated = true, deprecated_since = "vala-0.26", replacement = "activate_callback")]
        public unowned GLib.SimpleActionActivateCallback? activate;
        public weak string parameter_type;
        public weak string state;
        [Version (deprecated_since = "vala-0.26", replacement = "change_state_callback")]
        public unowned GLib.SimpleActionChangeStateCallback? change_state;
        [CCode (cname = "activate")]
        public unowned GLib.SimpleActionActivateFunc activate_callback;
        [CCode (cname = "change_state")]
        public unowned GLib.SimpleActionChangeStateFunc? change_state_callback;
    }

then compile your program. It no longer generates the g_action_entry_destroy () call for me.

At present ActionEntry is generated from the GIR with a custom modification in vapi/metadata/Gio-2.0-custom.vala. We could simply update that with the unowned delegates, but I also wonder why the other fields are marked as weak rather than unowned. The weak modifiers were added back in 2014: https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/vala/commit/8483484d092357bae2dc2eeb3abb448befe4f121

Ideally it would nice to remove the custom Vala code completely, but I'm not sure of the implications of that.

